  "A carry trade borrows yen at 0.1% to invest in Brazilian bonds at 10%. The approximate interest spread is:": "",
  "10%, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "5%, based on conventional assumptions about interest": "",
  "0.1%, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "Approximately 9.9%, but highly risky if exchange rates move adversely": "",
  "The carry trade profits from the interest rate differential: 10% - 0.1% = 9.9%. However, if the yen strengthens or the Brazilian real weakens, currency losses can quickly exceed the interest spread.": "",
  "What is a currency exchange rate?": "",
  "The price of one currency expressed in terms of another currency": "",
  "The rate at which currencies depreciate over time": "",
  "The fee charged by banks for currency transactions": "",
  "The interest rate set by a foreign central bank": "",
  "An exchange rate tells you how much one currency is worth in terms of another. For example, EUR/USD = 1.10 means 1 euro costs $1.10. Exchange rates fluctuate based on trade flows, interest rate differentials, and economic conditions.": "",
  "What is a carry trade?": "",
  "Carrying cash across international borders, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "Borrowing in a low-interest-rate currency and investing in a high-interest-rate currency to profit from the rate differential": "",
  "Buying stocks on margin given that prevailing carry conditions tend to reinforce this particular trajectory": "",
  "A long-term buy-and-hold strategy without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "Carry trades exploit interest rate differentials between countries. The strategy is profitable as long as exchange rates remain stable, but adverse currency movements can quickly wipe out gains.": "",
  "What are ADRs (American Depositary Receipts)?": "",
  "A record of international wire transfers": "",
  "A type of US government bond": "",
  "Certificates representing shares of foreign companies that trade on US exchanges in dollars": "",
  "Tax receipts from foreign investments": "",
  "ADRs allow US investors to buy shares of foreign companies on US stock exchanges, denominated in dollars. They eliminate the need to trade on foreign exchanges, though the underlying stock is still subject to currency risk.": "",
  "What is sovereign risk?": "",
  "Risk of a company going bankrupt": "",
  "Risk from investing in government bonds of developed nations": "",
  "The risk that a country's government will default on its debt, devalue its currency, or impose capital controls": "",
  "The risk of natural disasters": "",
  "Sovereign risk is the danger that a national government will fail to meet its financial obligations. This can include outright default, forced currency devaluation, or restrictions on capital leaving the country.": "",
  "What is Purchasing Power Parity (PPP)?": "",
  "A method for calculating GDP in most scenarios involving basket factors": "",
  "A measure of consumer spending habits, based on conventional assumptions about basket": "",
  "A theory stating that exchange rates should adjust so that identical goods cost the same in different countries": "",
  "A government subsidy program within the broader context of basket analysis": "",
  "PPP suggests that in the long run, exchange rates should equalize the price of an identical basket of goods across countries. The Big Mac Index is a popular informal PPP measure comparing burger prices worldwide.": "",
  "What is transfer pricing in international finance?": "",
  "The fee for transferring stock ownership, as the dynamics involved tend to push conditions in this direction over time": "",
  "The prices multinational corporations set for transactions between their own subsidiaries in different countries, affecting where profits are reported and taxes paid": "",
  "The price of converting currencies because the underlying forces at work tend to produce exactly this type of outcome": "",
  "The cost of transferring money between bank accounts when considering all relevant pricing factors": "",
  "Transfer pricing allows multinational corporations to allocate profits across countries by setting prices on internal transactions. Companies may use this to shift profits to low-tax jurisdictions, which is why tax authorities closely monitor transfer pricing.": "",
  "What are capital controls?": "",
  "Corporate budgeting rules": "",
  "Rules about how much capital a company must hold": "",
  "Government-imposed restrictions on the flow of money into or out of a country": "",
  "Regulations on capital gains taxes": "",
  "Capital controls are restrictions governments impose on cross-border financial flows. They can prevent foreign investors from withdrawing money, as seen during the Argentine crisis, trapping investor capital in the country.": "",
