  "A hedge fund runs a carry trade: borrows $10 million in Japanese yen at 0.5% and invests in Turkish lira bonds at 15%. If the Turkish lira depreciates 20% against the yen during the year, the fund's outcome is:": "",
  "A net loss of approximately 5.5% because the 20% currency depreciation more than wipes out the 14.5% interest spread": "",
  "A guaranteed profit because the interest rate spread is positive": "",
  "A 14.5% profit from the interest rate spread": "",
  "Break even": "",
  "Interest earned: 15% - 0.5% = 14.5%. Currency loss: -20%. Net result: approximately -5.5%. Carry trades are profitable when currencies are stable but can produce devastating losses when the high-yielding currency depreciates sharply.": "",
